  "prompt": "What are the rules for Yahoo's fantasy hockey?",
  "response": "Yahoo's fantasy hockey typically follows a standard set of rules, though specific league settings can vary based on how the league commissioner sets up the league. Here's a general overview of the rules and features commonly found in Yahoo Fantasy Hockey:\n\n1. **League Types**: \n   - **Public Leagues**: Open to all users and typically have standard settings.\n   - **Private Leagues**: Created by users and require an invitation to join. These leagues can have customized settings.\n\n2. **Drafting**:\n   - **Snake Draft**: Each team takes turns selecting players in a reverse order for each round.\n   - **Auction Draft**: Teams are given a budget to bid on players.\n\n3. **Roster Positions**: \n   - Typical roster spots include forwards (C, LW, RW), defensemen (D), goalies (G), and utility players (UTIL).\n   - Some leagues might have specific categories or additional positions depending on settings.\n\n4. **Scoring Categories**:\n   - Categories can include goals, assists, plus/minus, shots on goal, penalty minutes (PIM), power-play points, and more.\n   - Yahoo may use head-to-head or rotisserie formats to determine standings based on these stats.\n\n5. **Head-to-Head vs. Points**:\n   - **Head-to-Head**: Teams compete against each other each week, and points are awarded based on performance in various categories.\n   - **Points League**: Teams accumulate points based on players' performance, with each statistical category assigned a point value.\n\n6. **Player Transactions**:\n   - **Waivers**: Players who are not on a roster may be available through a waiver system that gives teams an opportunity to claim them based on their waiver priority.\n   - **Free Agents**: Players not on any team can be picked up without going through waivers.\n\n7. **Trades**:\n   - Players can trade with other teams. Trades may need to be accepted by both parties and can be subject to league voting or approval processes.\n\n8. **Injuries and IR Spots**:\n   - Teams may have Injury Reserve (IR) slots where they can stash injured players, allowing for roster flexibility.\n\n9. **Playoffs**: \n   - Many leagues have a playoff format based on the standings at the end of the regular season, where top teams compete for the league championship.\n\n10. **Season Length**: \n   - The fantasy season typically runs parallel to the NHL season and can vary by league.\n\n11. **Custom Settings**: \n   - League commissioners have the ability to customize various settings such as scoring categories, roster sizes, and more.\n\nIt's always a good idea to check the specific settings of the league you're participating in, as they could differ from these general guidelines. For the most accurate and detailed information, refer directly to Yahoo Fantasy Sports or your league's specific rules.",
